ğŸ“¦ What is a Pod?
A Pod is the smallest deployable unit in K8s, containing:
ğŸ”¸ One or more containers (like Docker) running together
ğŸ”¸ Ephemeral by nature â€“ Short-lived, replaceable
ğŸ”¸ Can be single-container (common) or multi-container (for tightly coupled apps)

ğŸ”‘ Key Points About Pods
âœ… K8s manages Pods, not containers directly
âœ… Pods need an image, config & resource limits at creation
âœ… Two ways to create Pods:
1ï¸ Imperative (kubectl commands) â€“ Quick & easy
kubectl run mypod --image=nginx

2ï¸ Declarative (YAML manifests) â€“ Best for reproducibility & version control
---
apiVersion: v1
kind: Pod
metadata:
 name: my-first-pod
spec:
 containers:
  - name: nginx
   image: nginx
   ports:
    - containerPort: 80
Apply with:
 kubectl apply -f demo.yaml
 
âš¡ Quick Minikube Setup Guide

1ï¸ Prep Your Environment
Launch an EC2 instance with
Instance Type: t2.medium (or equivalent)
Memory: 2+ CPUs, 2GB+ RAM
Storage: Min. 20GB (25GB recommended)
OS: Ubuntu/Linux preferred

2ï¸ Install Docker & Minikube
sudo apt install docker.io -y
curl -LO https://lnkd.in/enAERWWf
sudo install minikube-linux-amd64 /usr/local/bin/minikube

3ï¸ Start Minikube
minikube start --driver=docker --force

4ï¸ Verify Your Cluster
 kubectl get pods -A

